PIZZA SALES ANALYSIS PROJECT¶

Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

A moderately sized, locally popular food joint operates a chain of outlets located in a metropolitan area, offering a diverse menu of pizzas, sides, and beverages. Despite having a steady flow of customers, they face challenges in optimizing their order fulfillment process, leading to delays during peak hours, which results in customer dissatisfaction and impacts repeat business. Additionally, they struggle with inventory management, often experiencing shortages of popular ingredients or excess stock of less favored items. To address these issues, they are implementing a new order management system and seeking to analyze sales data to better predict demand and streamline inventory.

Objective¶

The business has engaged Steve Archuleta as a Data Analyst to enhance operational efficiency and boost customer satisfaction. Steve has been provided raw historical sales data and has been tasked with pre-processing historical sales data to uncover trends, building an interactive dashboard to enable visual reporting of key metrics, and generating email reports to communicate key insights to stakeholders. This analysis will enable the stakeholders to get a clearer understanding of the business, stay on top of changing market scenarios via frequent alerts, and make quick, informed decisions to resolve operational challenges. The anticipated outcomes include reduced order processing times, improved inventory turnover, and increased customer satisfaction leading to higher repeat sales.

Data Description:¶

This dataset contain detailed information about pizza orders, including specifics about the pizza variants, quantities, pricing, dates, times, and categorization details.

  • pizza_id: A unique identifier assigned to each distinct pizza variant available for ordering.
  • order_id: A unique identifier for each order made, which links to multiple pizzas.
  • pizza_name_id: An identifier linking to a specific name of the pizza.
  • quantity: The number of units of a specific pizza variant ordered within an order.
  • order_date: The date when the order was placed.
  • order_time: The time when the order was placed.
  • unit_price: The cost of a single unit of the specific pizza variant.
  • pizza_size: Represents the size of the pizza (e.g., small, medium, large).
  • pizza_category: Indicates the category of the pizza, such as vegetarian, non-vegetarian, etc.
  • pizza_name: Specifies the name of the specific pizza variant ordered.

# ========================================================================
# IMPORT THE REQUIRED AZURE ML MODULES TO MANAGE THE WORKSPACE AND COMPUTE
# ========================================================================
# from azure.ai.ml import MLClient
# from azure.identity import DefaultAzureCredential
# from azure.ai.ml.entities import AmlCompute

# =====================================================
# CREATE A DEFAULT CREDENTIAL OBJECT FOR AUTHENTICATION
# =====================================================
credential = DefaultAzureCredential()

# ==============================================================
# CREATE A MLCLIENT INSTANCE TO COMMUNICATE WITH AZURE WORKSPACE
# ==============================================================
ml_client = MLClient(
    credential=credential,
    subscription_id="af6e7bea-cbc6-4f83-ab20-3169af7fccdf",
    resource_group_name="default_resource_group",
    workspace_name="pizza-sales-intelligent-reporting"
)

# ==================================
# DEFINE THE NAME OF THE CPU CLUSTER
# ==================================
cpu_compute_target = "cpu-cluster"

# =======================================================
# CHECK IF THE CLUSTER ALREADY EXISTS OR CREATE A NEW ONE
# =======================================================
try:
    # ==== TRY TO GET EXISTING CLUSTER
    cpu_cluster = ml_client.compute.get(cpu_compute_target)
    print(f"ALREADY USING EXISTING CLUSTER NAMED {cpu_compute_target}.")
except Exception:
    print("CREATING A NEW CPU COMPUTE TARGET...")
    # ==== CREATE A NEW CPU CLUSTER WITH DEFINED PARAMETERS
    cpu_cluster = AmlCompute(
        name=cpu_compute_target,
        type="amlcompute",
        size="Standard_A2_v2",
        min_instances=0,
        max_instances=1,
        idle_time_before_scale_down=180,
        tier="Dedicated"
    )
    # ==== CREATE OR UPDATE THE CLUSTER IN AZURE ML WORKSPACE
    cpu_cluster = ml_client.compute.begin_create_or_update(cpu_cluster).result()
    print(f"COMPUTE CLUSTER {cpu_cluster.name} CREATED WITH SIZE {cpu_cluster.size}.")

  • A .yml FILE, OFTEN CALLED A YAML FILE, IS A CONFIGURATION FILE LISTING SOFTWARE DEPENDENCIES IN A STRUCTURED, HUMAN-READABLE FORMAT. IN THE GIVEN PIPELINE, THE conda.yml FILE SPECIFIES PYTHON VERSION AND PACKAGES NEEDED, ENSURING A CONSISTENT ENVIRONMENT FOR RUNNING CODE AND AVOIDING DEPENDENCY CONFLICTS.
  • A DOCKER IMAGE FILE IS A PACKAGED SNAPSHOT OF AN ENVIRONMENT, INCLUDING THE OPERATING SYSTEM, LIBRARIES, AND TOOLS. USING A PREDEFINED DOCKER IMAGE (LIKE A BASE IMAGE FROM mcr.microsoft.com/azureml) CREATES A CONSISTENT, PORTABLE ENVIRONMENT CAPABLE OF RUNNING THE PIPELINE SEAMLESSLY ACROSS DIFFERENT SYSTEMS, ENSURING REPRODUCIBILITY AND RELIABILITY.
  • CREATING AND REGISTERING THE DOCKER IMAGE FILE ENVIRONMENT WITH AZURE ML GRANTS THE MACHINE LEARNING PIPELINE A STABLE RUNTIME, ALLOWING CODE, DATA, AND DEPENDENCIES TO REMAIN CONSISTENT. THE CONFIGURED ENVIRONMENT FUNCTIONS LIKE A CONTROLLED LABORATORY SETUP, ENSURING COMPUTATIONS YIELD IDENTICAL RESULTS REGARDLESS OF LOCATION OR TIME OF EXECUTION.
  • EXECUTION OF ENVIRONMENT CREATION STEPS IS ESSENTIAL FOR A MACHINE LEARNING WORKFLOW: THE SPECIFIED CONFIGURATION DEFINES ALL REQUIRED PACKAGES, PYTHON LIBRARIES, AND EXTERNAL DEPENDENCIES IN ONE PLACE. THEREFORE, SUBSEQUENT PIPELINE STEPSSUCH AS DATA PREPROCESSING, MODEL TRAINING, OR INFERENCEOCCUR IN A CAREFULLY MANAGED AND PREDICTABLE ENVIRONMENT.

# ============================================
# HISTOGRAM FOR total_price, A NUMERIC FEATURE
# THE DISTRIBUTION OF TOTAL PRICE (REFORMATTED)
# ============================================

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
ax = sns.histplot(data=df, x='total_price', bins=30, kde=True, color="skyblue")

# ADD COUNTS ON TOP OF BARS
for p in ax.patches:
    ax.annotate(
        format(p.get_height(), '.0f'),  # Format count as integer
        (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()),
        ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10, color='black', xytext=(0, 5), textcoords='offset points'
    )

# ADD TITLE AND LABELS
plt.title("Distribution of Total Price", fontsize=16, pad=20)
plt.xlabel("Total Price (in $)", fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("Frequency", fontsize=12)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')

# DISPLAY THE PLOT
plt.show()
OBSERVATION
  • DISTRIBUTION IS HEAVILY CONCENTRATED BETWEEN APPROX. $9.75 AND $22, WITH MULTIPLE PEAKS IN THAT RANGE.
  • COUNTS ON TOP OF BARS SHOW HIGH FREQUENCY IN LOWER PRICE TIERS, INDICATING MOST ORDERS HAVE A TOTAL PRICE UNDER $20.
  • HIGHER PRICE POINTS ABOVE $30 ARE RARE, WITH VERY FEW ORDERS EXCEEDING THAT THRESHOLD.
  • THE KDE CURVE CONFIRMS A MULTI-MODAL DISTRIBUTION IN THE LOWER RANGE, SUGGESTING DISTINCT PRICE GROUPINGS.

# ===========================================================================
# HISTOGRAM FOR A LOG-TRANSFORMED total_price, A NUMERIC FEATURE
# IF TOTAL_PRICE IS SKEWED, APPLY LOG TRANSFORMATION TO IMPROVE VISUALIZATION
# ===========================================================================

log_total_price = np.log1p(df['total_price'])

# PLOT HISTOGRAM
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
ax = sns.histplot(x=log_total_price, bins=30, kde=True, color='salmon')

# ADD COUNTS ON TOP OF BARS
for p in ax.patches:
    ax.annotate(
        format(p.get_height(), '.0f'),  
        (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), 
        ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10, color='black', xytext=(0, 5), textcoords='offset points'
    )

# ADD TITLE AND LABELS
plt.title("Distribution of Log-Transformed Total Price", fontsize=16, pad=20)
plt.xlabel("Log(1 + Total Price)", fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("Frequency", fontsize=12)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')

# DISPLAY THE PLOT
plt.show()
OBSERVATION
  • APPLYING A LOG TRANSFORMATION COMPRESSES THE DISTRIBUTION, MAKING PRICE DIFFERENCES MORE VISUALLY COMPARABLE.
  • MULTIPLE PEAKS ARE STILL EVIDENT, SUGGESTING DISTINCT PRICE CLUSTERS REMAIN EVEN AFTER TRANSFORMATION.
  • HIGH COUNTS IN THE LOWER LOG RANGE INDICATE THE MAJORITY OF ORDERS STILL CLUSTER AT LOWER PRICE LEVELS.
  • EXTREMELY HIGH VALUES ARE RELATIVELY SCARCE, AS INDICATED BY FEW BARS AT THE UPPER END OF THE LOG SCALE.

# ===========================================================
# BOX PLOT FOR unit_price, A NUMERIC FEATURE
# HELPS TO DETECT OUTLIERS AND UNDERSTAND DISTRIBUTION SPREAD
# EMULATING THE GIVEN BOX PLOT FORMAT
# ===========================================================

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 12))  # Adjust figure size for vertical orientation
ax = sns.boxplot(y='unit_price', data=df, color="lightgreen", width=0.3)

# CALCULATE STATISTICS
median = df['unit_price'].median()
mean = df['unit_price'].mean()

# ADD MEAN AND MEDIAN LINES
plt.axhline(median, color='blue', linestyle='--', label=f'Median: ${median:.2f}')
plt.axhline(mean, color='red', linestyle='--', label=f'Mean: ${mean:.2f}')

# ADD LEGEND, TITLE, AND LABELS
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.title("Boxplot of Unit Price", fontsize=16, pad=20)
plt.xlabel("")  # Not needed for a vertical boxplot
plt.ylabel("Unit Price", fontsize=12)

# DISPLAY THE PLOT
plt.show()
OBSERVATION
  • THE BOX REPRESENTS THE MIDDLE 50% OF UNIT PRICES, INDICATING THAT THE BULK OF PRICES ARE BETWEEN APPROX. $13 AND $20.
  • THE MEDIAN (~$16.50, BLUE LINE) IS VERY CLOSE TO THE MEAN (~$16.49, RED LINE), SUGGESTING A RELATIVELY SYMMETRIC DISTRIBUTION OF UNIT PRICES.
  • OUTLIERS ARE PRESENT ABOVE APPROX. $35, INDICATING RARELY OCCURRING HIGH-PRICE ITEMS.
  • THE WHISKERS SHOW THAT MOST DATA FALLS WITHIN ~$10 AND ~$25, REFLECTING A MODERATE RANGE OF UNIT PRICES.

)

        color="black", va="center", fontsize=10
    )

# =====================================================
# FEATURE EXTRACTION FOR CATEGORICAL/TEXTUAL DATA
# INGREDIENTS: COUNT FREQUENCY OF INDIVIDUAL INGREDIENTS
# =====================================================

# THE GOAL:
# - DETERMINE THE CORRECT DELIMITER (" ,") FOR INGREDIENTS
# - SPLIT THE 'pizza_ingredients' COLUMN INTO INDIVIDUAL INGREDIENTS
# - CHECK IF THERE ARE LEADING/TRAILING SPACES
# - CLEAN AND STANDARDIZE THE INGREDIENT NAMES
# - COUNT FREQUENCY OF EACH INGREDIENT

# IMPORTANT NOTE:
# INITIAL ATTEMPTS SHOWED THAT SPLITTING BY JUST "," LEFT LEADING SPACES.
# THEREFORE, THE CHOSEN DELIMITER IS ", " (COMMA + SPACE) FOR A CLEANER SEPARATION.
In [31]:
# ============================================================

# SPLIT THE 'pizza_ingredients' COLUMN BY ", " (COMMA + SPACE)
# THEN EXPLODE THE LISTS INTO INDIVIDUAL ROWS

all_ingredients = (
    df['pizza_ingredients']
    .apply(lambda x: x.split(', '))  # split by comma + space for cleaner separation
    .explode()                       # transform lists into separate rows
)

# ====================================================
# //EXTRACT MONTH FROM order_time INTO order_month
# //CLASSIFY order_time INTO time_of_day BASED ON HOUR:
# //     MORNING = 6 < HOUR < 12
# //     AFTERNOON = 12 < HOUR < 18
# //     EVENING = OTHERWISE
# //DISPLAY FIRST FEW ROWS OF MODIFIED DATAFRAME
# ====================================================
df['order_month'] = df['order_time'].dt.month

df['time_of_day'] = df['order_time'].dt.hour.apply(
    lambda x: "Morning" if 6 < x < 12 
    else ("Afternoon" if 12 < x < 18 
    else "Evening")
)

# =========================================================
# IDENTIFY OUTLIERS USING THE INTERQUARTILE RANGE (IQR)
# POINTS BEYOND 1.5 * IQR ABOVE Q3 OR BELOW Q1 ARE OUTLIERS
# =========================================================
Q1 = df['total_price'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df['total_price'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

print("Q1:", Q1)
print("Q3:", Q3)
print('\n')
print("IQR:", IQR)
print('\n')
print("Lower Bound:", lower_bound)
print("Upper Bound:", upper_bound)
print('\n')
# COUNT OUTLIERS
outliers_lower = (df['total_price'] < lower_bound).sum()
outliers_upper = (df['total_price'] > upper_bound).sum()

print("Number of Outliers Above Upper Bound:", outliers_upper)

# ==========================================================
# PRINCIPAL COMPONENT ANALYSIS (PCA) FOR DIMENSION REDUCTION
# REDUCE NUMERIC FEATURES TO TWO PRINCIPAL COMPONENTS
# PLOT THE FIRST TWO COMPONENTS WITH HUE AS pizza_category
# ==========================================================
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

numeric_features = df[['quantity', 'unit_price', 'total_price']].dropna()
scaled_data = StandardScaler().fit_transform(numeric_features)

pca = PCA(n_components=2)
pca_components = pca.fit_transform(scaled_data)

pca_df = pd.DataFrame(pca_components, columns=['PC1', 'PC2'])
pca_df['pizza_category'] = df.loc[numeric_features.index, 'pizza_category']

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
ax = sns.scatterplot(x='PC1', y='PC2', hue='pizza_category', data=pca_df, palette='Set2', alpha=0.7)

plt.title("PCA SCATTER PLOT: REDUCED DIMENSIONS WITH CATEGORY HUE")
plt.xlabel("PRINCIPAL COMPONENT 1")
plt.ylabel("PRINCIPAL COMPONENT 2")
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')

# Add annotation explaining PCA in the lower right quadrant
annotation_text = (
    "PCA (Principal Component Analysis) reduces high-dimensional data\n"
    "into fewer components (PC1, PC2) capturing the most variance.\n"
    " PC1 & PC2 are new axes that explain the largest trends in data.\n"
    " This scatterplot shows data spread in just two dimensions,\n"
    "  making patterns easier to visualize.\n"
    " By coloring points by category, we can see if certain categories\n"
    "  cluster together or separate out along these principal axes."
)

# Get current axis limits
x_min, x_max = ax.get_xlim()
y_min, y_max = ax.get_ylim()

# Place annotation in lower right quadrant
ax.text(
    x_max*0.3, y_min*0.6,   # Adjust these multipliers as needed to position text
    annotation_text,
    fontsize=10,
    color="black",
    va="bottom",
    ha="left",
    bbox=dict(boxstyle="round,pad=0.3", fc="white", ec="black", alpha=0.8)
)

plt.show()
OBSERVATION
  • AFTER REDUCING THE DATA TO TWO PRINCIPAL COMPONENTS (PC1 AND PC2), EACH POINT REPRESENTS A PIZZA ORDER THAT HAS BEEN PLOTTED ACCORDING TO THE MOST SIGNIFICANT PATTERNS CAPTURED IN THE NUMERIC FEATURES (quantity, unit_price, total_price).
  • EVEN THOUGH THE ORIGINAL DATA WAS MULTIDIMENSIONAL, THE PLOT SHOWS THAT CERTAIN PIZZA CATEGORIES TEND TO GROUP TOGETHER ALONG THESE NEW AXES. FOR EXAMPLE, IF Classic and Veggie TEND TO CLUSTER IN A SIMILAR AREA, IT SUGGESTS THEIR ORDERS SHARE COMMON TRAITS IN PRICE AND QUANTITY PATTERNS.
  • PC1 AND PC2 DONT REPRESENT DIRECT FACTORS LIKE PRICE OR SIZE, BUT RATHER NEW DIMENSIONS THAT COMBINE THESE FEATURES TO EXPLAIN THE MOST VARIANCE IN THE DATASET. ORDERS THAT APPEAR CLOSER TOGETHER LIKELY HAVE SIMILAR SPENDING LEVELS AND PRODUCT MIXES, WHILE THOSE FAR APART MAY REFLECT DISTINCT ORDERING BEHAVIORS.
  • COLORING THE POINTS BY pizza_category HELPS DETERMINE IF CERTAIN CATEGORIES GRAVITATE TOWARDS PARTICULAR REGIONS IN THIS PCA SPACE. IF A SPECIFIC CATEGORY CONSISTENTLY PLOTS HIGHER ON PC2 OR FARTHER ALONG PC1, THAT SUGGESTS ITS ORDERS MIGHT DIFFER IN KEY WAYS FROM OTHER CATEGORIES (E.G., TYPICALLY MORE EXPENSIVE OR TYPICALLY LARGER IN QUANTITY).

# =====================================================================
# RADAR/POLAR PLOT (PARALLEL CATEGORIES) FOR MULTIVARIATE VIEW
# COMPARE MEAN FEATURES ACROSS MULTIPLE pizza_categories
# AGGREGATE MEAN OF quantity, unit_price, total_price FOR EACH CATEGORY
# THEN NORMALIZE AND PLOT ON A RADAR CHART
# =====================================================================


# ==== CALCULATE MEAN OF SELECTED NUMERIC FEATURES BY pizza_category
radar_data = df.groupby('pizza_category')[['quantity','unit_price','total_price']].mean()

# ==== NORMALIZE THE VALUES TO RANGE [0,1] FOR RADAR PLOT
radar_data_norm = (radar_data - radar_data.min()) / (radar_data.max() - radar_data.min())
categories = radar_data_norm.columns.tolist()
N = len(categories)

# ==== RADAR CHART SETUP
angles = [n / float(N) * 2 * np.pi for n in range(N)]
angles += angles[:1]

plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
ax = plt.subplot(111, polar=True)

for cat in radar_data_norm.index:
    values = radar_data_norm.loc[cat].values.flatten().tolist()
    values += values[:1]
    ax.plot(angles, values, label=cat, linewidth=2)
    ax.fill(angles, values, alpha=0.1)

ax.set_xticks(angles[:-1])
ax.set_xticklabels(categories)
ax.set_yticklabels([])
ax.set_title("RADAR PLOT: COMPARING FEATURES ACROSS CATEGORIES (MULTIVARIATE)")
ax.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(0.6,0.7))
plt.show()
OBSERVATION
  • A RADAR PLOT IS A WAY TO VISUALIZE MULTIPLE VARIABLES FOR DIFFERENT CATEGORIES ON A SINGLE CHART. EACH AXIS REPRESENTS ONE FEATURE, AND ALL AXES RADIATE OUT FROM THE CENTER, ALLOWING DIRECT COMPARISONS OF CATEGORY "SHAPES" ACROSS MULTIPLE DIMENSIONS.
  • NORMALIZING THE MEAN VALUES (SCALING THEM BETWEEN 0 AND 1) ENSURES THAT EACH FEATURE IS MEASURED ON THE SAME RELATIVE SCALE. THIS PREVENTS ANY SINGLE FEATURE WITH INHERENTLY LARGER VALUES FROM DOMINATING THE PLOT, MAKING IT EASIER TO SEE RELATIVE DIFFERENCES BETWEEN CATEGORIES.
  • IN THIS RADAR PLOT, EACH PIZZA CATEGORY IS REPRESENTED BY A POLYGON FORMED BY CONNECTING POINTS ON THE AXES FOR quantity, unit_price, AND total_price. OBSERVING THE SHAPE AND SIZE OF EACH POLYGON HELPS IDENTIFY WHICH CATEGORIES TEND TO HAVE HIGHER OR LOWER NORMALIZED VALUES FOR THESE FEATURES.
  • FOR EXAMPLE, IF THE POLYGON FOR THE "CHICKEN" CATEGORY EXTENDS FURTHER ALONG THE unit_price AXIS, IT INDICATES THAT CHICKEN PIZZAS HAVE RELATIVELY HIGHER UNIT PRICES COMPARED TO OTHER CATEGORIES. SIMILARLY, A CATEGORY'S POLYGON THAT IS SMALLER OR CLOSER TO THE CENTER ON ALL AXES SUGGESTS THAT IT GENERALLY RANKS LOWER ACROSS THESE NORMALIZED MEAN FEATURES.
  • BY COMPARING THESE POLYGON SHAPES, VIEWERS CAN QUICKLY SEE PATTERNS: MAYBE ONE CATEGORY CONSISTENTLY SCORES HIGHER ON total_price, WHILE ANOTHER BALANCES OUT BETWEEN quantity AND unit_price. THE RADAR CHARTS ABILITY TO DISPLAY MULTIVARIATE DATA IN A SIMPLE, COMPARATIVE MANNER HELPS IDENTIFY WHICH CATEGORIES STAND OUT, WHICH ARE SIMILAR, AND WHERE POTENTIAL OPPORTUNITIES OR ANOMALIES LIE.

# ====================================================
# CREATE A DIRECTORY TO STORE THE PREPROCESSING SCRIPT
# ====================================================
src_dir_job_scripts = "./project_scripts"
os.makedirs(src_dir_job_scripts, exist_ok=True)

# ===============================================================
# WRITE THE PRE_PROCESS.PY SCRIPT TO PROCESS THE PIZZA SALES DATA
# ===============================================================
preprocess_script_content = r'''
# =========================
# IMPORT REQUIRED LIBRARIES
# =========================
import argparse
import pandas as pd
from pathlib import Path
import numpy as np

# =============================================
# DEFINE A FUNCTION TO MAP HOURS TO TIME OF DAY
# =============================================
def map_time_of_day(x):
    # ==== IF HOUR BETWEEN 6 AND 12 => MORNING
    # ==== IF HOUR BETWEEN 12 AND 18 => AFTERNOON
    # ==== OTHERWISE => EVENING
    if 6 < x < 12:
        return "Morning"
    elif 12 < x < 18:
        return "Afternoon"
    else:
        return "Evening"

if __name__ == "__main__":
    # ==========================================
    # PARSE ARGUMENTS FOR INPUT AND OUTPUT PATHS
    # ==========================================
    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser()
    parser.add_argument("--data", type=str, help="PATH TO INPUT DATA")
    parser.add_argument("--output", type=str, help="PATH TO OUTPUT DATA")
    args = parser.parse_args()

    # ===========================================
    # READ THE INPUT DATA FROM THE SPECIFIED PATH
    # ===========================================
    df = pd.read_csv(args.data)

    # =================
    # REMOVE DUPLICATES
    # =================
    df = df.drop_duplicates()

    # ==========================================================
    # HANDLE MISSING VALUES BY DROPPING ROWS WITH MISSING VALUES
    # (ADJUST AS NEEDED FOR BUSINESS LOGIC)
    # ==========================================================
    df = df.dropna()

    # ==============================================================
    # CREATE A SINGLE DATETIME COLUMN FROM order_date AND order_time
    # 'format="mixed"' IS A PLACEHOLDER; USE APPROPRIATE PARSING LOGIC
    # ==============================================================
    df['order_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['order_date'] + " " + df['order_time'], errors='coerce')

    # ========================================================
    # DROP THE order_date COLUMN AFTER MERGING INTO order_time
    # ========================================================
    df.drop(columns=['order_date'], inplace=True)

    # ==================================================
    # EXTRACT THE MONTH FROM order_time INTO order_month
    # ==================================================
    df['order_month'] = df['order_time'].dt.month

    # ====================================================
    # MAP THE HOUR OF order_time TO A TIME_OF_DAY CATEGORY
    # ====================================================
    df['time_of_day'] = df['order_time'].dt.hour.apply(map_time_of_day)

    # ===============================================================
    # //ONE-HOT ENCODE THE pizza_category COLUMN FOR BETTER MODEL INPUT
    # //AVOID ARTIFICIAL ORDERING ON CATEGORIES
    # //CREATE NEW BINARY INDICATOR COLUMNS
    # ===============================================================
    # Instead of overwriting df directly with get_dummies:
    temp_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df["pizza_category"], prefix="category", drop_first=False)
    df = pd.concat([df, temp_dummies], axis=1)
    # NOTE: do not drop df["pizza_category"] or daily_email_report.py will fail
    # df = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=['pizza_category'], prefix='category', drop_first=False)

    # ===================================================
    # DEFINE THE OUTPUT PATHS AND SAVE THE PROCESSED DATA
    # ===================================================
    output_data_store = args.output
    preprocessed_data_output_path = Path(output_data_store, "processed_data.csv")
    df.to_csv(preprocessed_data_output_path, index=False)
'''

with open(os.path.join(src_dir_job_scripts, "pre_process.py"), "w") as f:
    f.write(preprocess_script_content)
OBSERVATION
  • THIS CODE BLOCK CREATES A DIRECTORY AND WRITES A PREPROCESSING SCRIPT NAMED pre_process.py. THE SCRIPT EXECUTES DATA CLEANING, DERIVES NEW FEATURES LIKE order_month AND time_of_day, AND ENSURES THAT RAW PIZZA SALES DATA IS PREPARED FOR SUBSEQUENT STEPS IN THE MACHINE LEARNING PIPELINE.
  • ALTHOUGH NO DIRECT OUTPUT APPEARS HERE, THE EXECUTION OF THESE STEPS FORMS A FOUNDATION FOR A REPRODUCIBLE, RELIABLE ANALYTICAL WORKFLOW, IMPROVING OVERALL DATA PROCESSING CONSISTENCY.
  • THE ADDITION OF ONE-HOT ENCODING FOR THE pizza_category FEATURE CREATES MULTIPLE BINARY INDICATOR COLUMNS, ONE FOR EACH CATEGORY. THIS APPROACH ENSURES THAT NO ARTIFICIAL ORDERING IS IMPOSED ON CATEGORIES, FACILITATING MORE ACCURATE MODELING AND ANALYSIS BY TREATING EACH CATEGORY AS A DISTINCT, INDEPENDENT FEATURE.
  • THE COMBINATION OF DATA CLEANING, FEATURE ENGINEERING, AND ONE-HOT ENCODING PRODUCES A HIGH-QUALITY, STRUCTURED DATASET SUITABLE FOR TRAINING MODELS AND CONDUCTING DETAILED ANALYSES WITHOUT INTRODUCING BIASES OR MISLEADING NUMERIC RELATIONSHIPS BETWEEN CATEGORIES.
  • THE RESULT IS AN AUTOMATED, PORTABLE, AND SCALABLE PREPROCESSING STEP THAT CAN BE REUSED AS THE PIPELINE EVOLVES, ENSURING THAT FUTURE WORKLOADS RECEIVE THE SAME WELL-PREPARED DATA FOUNDATION.

  • ALTHOUGH NO IMMEDIATE VISUAL OUTPUT APPEARS FROM DEFINING THIS COMMAND COMPONENT AND ENVIRONMENT, THESE STEPS LAY THE FOUNDATION FOR A REPEATABLE, AUTOMATED ML PIPELINE. DEFINING THE ENVIRONMENT AND COMMAND COMPONENT IN THIS MANNER HELPS TO STREAMLINE SUBSEQUENT STEPS, SUCH AS DATA PREPROCESSING, MODEL TRAINING, AND DEPLOYMENT, WITHOUT INTRODUCING CONFLICTS OR INCONSISTENCIES IN DEPENDENCIES.

app_py_content = r'''
# =========================
# IMPORT REQUIRED LIBRARIES
# =========================
import streamlit as st
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd


# ========================================
# DEFINE A FUNCTION TO LOAD PROCESSED DATA
# ========================================
def load_data():
    df = pd.read_csv("processed_data.csv")
    return df


# ================================
# DEFINE THE STREAMLIT APPLICATION
# ================================
def app():
    # ==== SET THE TITLE OF THE DASHBOARD
    st.title("Pizza Sales Data Analysis Dashboard")

    # ==== LOAD PROCESSED DATA
    df = load_data()
    df = pd.DataFrame(df)

    # ==== CALCULATE KEY METRICS
    total_orders = df['order_id'].nunique()
    total_revenue = df['total_price'].sum()
    most_popular_size = df['pizza_size'].value_counts().idxmax()
    most_frequent_category = df['pizza_category'].value_counts().idxmax()
    total_pizzas_sold = df['quantity'].sum()

    # ==== CREATE A SIDEBAR FOR KEY METRICS
    st.sidebar.header("Key Metrics")
    st.sidebar.metric("Total Orders", total_orders)
    st.sidebar.metric("Total Revenue", f"${total_revenue:,.2f}")
    st.sidebar.metric("Most Popular Size", most_popular_size)
    st.sidebar.metric("Most Popular Category", most_frequent_category)
    st.sidebar.metric("Total Pizzas Sold", total_pizzas_sold)

    # ==== DEFINE PLOTS TO DISPLAY
    plots = [
        {"title": "Top Selling Pizzas (by Quantity)", "x": "pizza_name", "y": "quantity", "top": 5},
        {"title": "Quantity of Pizzas Sold by Category and Time of the Day", "x": "time_of_day", "hue": "pizza_category"},
        {"title": "Quantity of Pizzas Sold by Size and Time of the Day", "x": "time_of_day", "hue": "pizza_size"},
        {"title": "Monthly Revenue Trends by Pizza Category", "x": "order_month", "y": "total_price", "hue": "pizza_category", "estimator": "sum", "marker": "o"}
    ]

    # ==== ITERATE OVER THE PLOTS AND RENDER THEM
    for plot in plots:
        st.header(plot["title"])
        fig, ax = plt.subplots()
        if "Top Selling Pizzas" in plot["title"]:
            data_aux = df.groupby(plot["x"])[plot["y"]].sum().reset_index().sort_values(by=plot["y"], ascending=False).head(plot["top"])
            ax.bar(data_aux[plot["x"]].values.tolist(), data_aux[plot["y"]].values.tolist())
        elif "Quantity of Pizzas" in plot["title"]:
            sns.countplot(data=df, x=plot["x"], hue=plot["hue"], ax=ax)
        elif "Monthly Revenue" in plot["title"]:
            sns.lineplot(data=df, x=plot["x"], y=plot["y"], hue=plot["hue"], estimator=plot["estimator"], errorbar=None, marker=plot["marker"], ax=ax)
        
        ax.set_xlabel(" ".join(plot["x"].split("_")).capitalize())
        if "y" in plot.keys():
            ax.set_ylabel(" ".join(plot["y"].split("_")).capitalize())
        else:
            ax.set_ylabel("Quantity")
        ax.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1,1))
        st.pyplot(fig)


# =====================
# RUN THE STREAMLIT APP
# =====================
if __name__ == "__main__":
    app()
'''

with open(os.path.join(src_dir_hf_space, "app.py"), "w") as f:
    f.write(app_py_content)

        <p>Regards,<br>Analytics Team</p>
        """
        return email_content

    # ==========================================
    # DEFINE A FUNCTION TO SEND THE EMAIL REPORT
    # ==========================================
    def send_email_report(email_config, report_metrics):
        email_content = create_email_content(report_metrics)
        server = smtplib.SMTP(email_config['smtp_server'], email_config['smtp_port'])
        server.starttls()
        server.login(email_config['sender_email'], email_config['password'])
        msg = MIMEMultipart()
        msg['From'] = email_config['sender_email']
        msg['To'] = email_config['receiver_emails']
        msg['Subject'] = 'Pizza Sales Analysis Report'
        msg.attach(MIMEText(email_content, 'html'))
        text = msg.as_string()
        server.sendmail(email_config['sender_email'], email_config['receiver_emails'], text)
        print(f"EMAIL REPORT SENT TO {email_config['receiver_emails']} SUCCESSFULLY!")
        server.quit()

    # ==========================================
    # CALL THE FUNCTION TO SEND THE EMAIL REPORT
    # ==========================================
    send_email_report(email_config, report)
'''

with open(os.path.join(src_dir_job_scripts, "daily_email_report.py"), "w") as f:
    f.write(email_script_content)
OBSERVATION
  • THIS CODE BLOCK CREATES A PYTHON SCRIPT THAT SENDS EMAIL REPORTS UPON COMPLETION OF DATA PROCESSING STEPS. THE SCRIPT DEFINES CREDENTIALS, AUTHENTICATES WITH GMAIL SERVERS, AND SENDS AUTOMATED REPORTS HIGHLIGHTING KEY METRICS FROM THE PROCESSED DATASET.
  • THE FUNCTION send_email_report SERVES A CRITICAL PURPOSE. THE email_config DICTIONARY ONLY DEFINES CREDENTIALS AND SMTP SETTINGS. THE DEDICATED FUNCTION EXECUTES THE ACTUAL SEND OPERATION, BUILDING THE MIME MESSAGE AND TRANSFERRING THE REPORT THROUGH THE SMTP CONNECTION. WITHOUT THIS FUNCTION, MERELY DEFINING CONFIGURATIONS WOULD NOT INITIATE ANY EMAIL TRANSMISSION.
  • THIS SETUP IS SUITABLE FOR INTEGRATION INTO A MACHINE LEARNING PIPELINE. THE DEFINED SCRIPT, ARGUMENT PARSING, AND REPORT GENERATION STEPS FACILITATE AUTOMATED NOTIFICATIONS ONCE DATA PROCESSING CONCLUDES. THESE ACTIONS ENHANCE PIPELINE OBSERVABILITY AND COMMUNICATION BY STREAMLINING THE DELIVERY OF INSIGHTS TO STAKEHOLDERS.

# DEFINE THE PIPELINE FUNCTION
# ============================
@dsl.pipeline(
    compute='cpu-cluster',
    description="PROJECT - INTELLIGENT REPORTING PIPELINE FOR PIZZA SALES"
)

def project_pipeline_(pipeline_job_data_input, hugging_face_folders):
    
    #A. ==== JOB 1: DATA PREPARATION JOB
    data_prep_job = step_process_pre_process(data=pipeline_job_data_input)

    #B. ==== JOB 2: HUGGING FACE AUTHENTICATION AND FILE PUSH JOB
    hugging_face_job = step_hugging_auth(
        processed_data_push=data_prep_job.outputs.processed_data,
        streamlit_files=hugging_face_folders
    )

    #C. ==== JOB 3: EMAIL REPORTING JOB
    # event_job is email_job... consider changing this variable name
    event_job = step_process_report(
        processed_data=data_prep_job.outputs.processed_data
    )

    # ==== RETURN PIPELINE OUTPUTS
    return {"pipeline_job_prep_data": data_prep_job.outputs.processed_data}

FINAL COMMENTS | Sample Output¶

1. Conclusions and Recommendations¶

FINAL COMMENTS, INSIGHTS, RECOMMENDATIONS, AND CONCLUSIONS

Problem Statement & Business Context Recap
A metropolitan-based pizza chain is grappling with operational hurdles: order fulfillment delays during peak hours leading to customer dissatisfaction, and difficulties with inventory management resulting in shortages or overstocking. By analyzing historical pizza sales data, the business aims to better predict demand, ensure efficient inventory turnover, and improve overall customer satisfaction. The ultimate objective is to reduce operational bottlenecks by automating and optimizing data-driven insights, from pre-processing steps through real-time reporting and stakeholder communication.

Data Description
The dataset comprises approximately 48,620 records, each containing details about pizza orders, including pizza identifiers, order identifiers, dates, times, prices, sizes, categories, and ingredient lists. Through thorough exploratory analysis and feature engineering, the project prepared these raw data into a structured, ready-to-use dataset, ensuring robust time-based features and correct handling of outliers, data types, and categorical variables.

Key Observations and Project Flow

  1. Data Pre-Processing and Cleansing

    • The data required careful cleaning to remove duplicates, handle missing values, and unify date and time columns into a single comprehensive order timestamp.
    • One-hot encoding was applied to the pizza_category feature to prevent imposing any artificial numeric ordering.

  2. Feature Engineering

    • Creation of month-based and time-of-day features allowed the pipeline to support seasonal and hourly demand analyses.
    • Aggregations confirmed that most orders have a quantity of 1, but occasional larger orders do exist, highlighting potential spikes in resource use.

  3. Statistical Insights

    • Unit prices clustered around a $16 average, while total prices occasionally spikedimportant for identifying high-value or group orders.
    • Correlation between unit_price and total_price was relatively strong; quantity also influenced total_price, although fewer orders exceed a quantity of 2.

  4. Visual and Interactive Dashboard

    • A Streamlit dashboard was created to allow interactive exploration of best-selling pizzas, time-of-day sales, and monthly trends.
    • Visuals, including boxplots, scatterplots, and heatmaps, exposed patterns such as the popularity of Classic category pizzas and the prevalence of size L.

  5. Hugging Face Integration

    • A pipeline step authenticates with Hugging Face and uploads the processed data plus the dashboard script. This ensures reproducible sharing and an external space for collaboration.

  6. Automated Email Alerts

    • A final pipeline step automatically emails key metrics (such as total revenue or most popular pizza sizes) to stakeholders, offering near-real-time insight into sales fluctuations and inventory considerations.

Conclusions and Recommendations

  • Demand Prediction and Inventory Strategy

    • Because outliers largely represent multi-item or large-size orders, more sophisticated demand forecasting models could separate normal from peak-hour group orders. The business can then prepare for short bursts of heavy ordering by allocating staff and ingredients accordingly.
    • Daily or weekly patterns (notably more evening orders) indicate a need for upscaled evening staffing and reallocation of resources to reduce wait times.

  • Menu Refinement

    • Data strongly suggests that certain pizza categories (like Classic and Supreme) and certain sizes (especially L) lead to higher or more stable revenue. Management can refine menus or promotions around these consistently popular options.
    • Low-frequency categories or ingredients might be re-evaluated: some rarely used ingredients could be replaced or made specialty items to reduce waste.

  • Enhancing Customer Satisfaction

    • With the validated time-of-day feature, the business can run targeted promotions in low-demand times (morning, early afternoon) to smooth out labor and ingredient usage.
    • Quicker fulfillment at peak times (late afternoon and evening) can be achieved by pre-assembly stations or improved queue management.

  • Operational Next Steps

    • Deploy a refined pipeline that integrates real-time ordering data and triggers rapid inventory updates and staff notifications.
    • Expand the pipeline to incorporate a more detailed segmentation: for instance, analyzing large events or group orders separately.
    • Continue collecting new data (like customer satisfaction ratings or promotional details) to strengthen predictive modeling and better align with consumer preferences.

By coupling data exploration, pipeline-driven automation, demand forecasting, and interactive reporting, the business can systematically address its operational challenges. The recommended approach is to maintain and enhance these pipeline stepsensuring the dataset and models remain updatedso that every stage, from pre-processing to final email reporting, continues to empower data-driven decisions. Long term, these measures are poised to reduce wait times, optimize ingredients, and improve customer loyalty through a more streamlined, responsive pizza ordering experience.
